data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9 (.NET 9), the Cosmos DB provider stopped supporting synchronous APIs by default, throwing `InvalidOperationException`. The `EnableSyncOverAsync()` opt-in was added as a **temporary bridge**.

**In EF Core 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All four methods in your repository will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there is no workaround except going async.

## How to fix it

Convert your repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- `async`/`await` throughout
- Convention: suffix method names with `Async`

Note that `async` will propagate up the call chain — all callers must also become async (up to the controller actions, which ASP.NET Core already supports as `async Task<IActionResult>`).
